Is there a philosophical reason why you haven't implemented multiple given statements across an inheritance hierarchy?

I'm thinking of a situation like this:

```python
class with_fake_http:
    
     def given_an_http_client(self):
           httpretty.register_uri('myserver.com/*')
           httpretty.enable()

     def cleanup_httpretty(self):
           httpretty.reset()
           httpretty.cleanup()

     def fake_response(self, uri, body):
            ...

class when_fetching_a_widget(with_fake_http):
   
        def given_a_widget(self):
            self.fake_response('/widgets/1', {id: 'widget-1'})

        def because_we_fetch_the_widget(self):
            self.widget = requests.get('myserver.com/widgets/1')

        def it_should_have_the_correct_id(self):
           ...
```

Basically, I want to set up some infrastructural concerns in a parent class, so that the actual context can focus purely on the scenario under test. Obviously I can fix it by calling a method on my parent class in each context, but that feels like a smell.

Currently if you have a form name such as: `example[0]['test']` you get back this from querystring-parser:

```
{
    "example": {
        "0": {
            "test": "fest"
        }
    }
}
```

It would be much better if it returned this instead:

```
{
    "example": [
        {
            "test": "fest"
        }
    ]
}
```

This isn't a HUGE issue, but its fairly annoying. If I get some time, I'll submit a pull request to solve this.

If anyone comes here looking for it here's the relevant bit:

```python
class AutoSingleRelatedObjectDescriptor(SingleRelatedObjectDescriptor):
    """
    The descriptor that handles the object creation for an AutoOneToOneField.
    """
    def __get__(self, instance, instance_type=None):
        model = getattr(self.related, 'related_model', self.related.model)

        try:
            return (super(AutoSingleRelatedObjectDescriptor, self)
                    .__get__(instance, instance_type))
        except model.DoesNotExist:
            obj = model(**{self.related.field.name: instance})

            obj.save()

            # Don't return obj directly, otherwise it won't be added
            # to Django's cache, and the first 2 calls to obj.relobj
            # will return 2 different in-memory objects
            return (super(AutoSingleRelatedObjectDescriptor, self)
                    .__get__(instance, instance_type))
```

@jensens @vangheem @hvelarde 

Would you have opinion on plone.app.tiles' ``plone.app.tiles``-registry key?

I believe, it is supposed to list "currently enabled tiles". The only place it's currently used is "Add new tile"-form, which has not been used since some early Deco versions. I'm using it on a custom app based on early package versions, but would not mind seeing it go away. I feel it only complicates the stack, because all real use cases seem to require additional ways to define available tiles.

for >= 3.2.0 versions Tower CLI is now composed of 2 parts: python clientlib and CLI wrapper around it. Since clientlib is almost totally dependent on AWX API, it would be great if clientlib can be generated out of AWX API, so that
* Instead of making code changes, getting up-to-date with AWX API can be as simple as updating spec YAML/JSON file;
* Users have the freedom to have their customized Tower CLI by providing their own spec files.
* Users get extra bonuses, like async API calls, depending on the client generating library used.

General procedure of migration:
* Describe AWX API as a an OpenAPI spec file, according to [OpenAPI spec](https://github.com/OAI/OpenAPI-Specification/blob/master/versions/3.0.1.md);
* Choose a code generating lib to generate clientlib (popular clientlibs like [swagger codegen](https://github.com/swagger-api/swagger-codegen), [bravado](https://github.com/Yelp/bravado) and [pyswagger](https://github.com/mission-liao/pyswagger));
* Refactor wrapping CLI code to accomodate to clientlib.

Hi guys,

I am adding integration tests to gcloud-java's datastore module. When I run this code:
```Java
datastore.add(ENTITY1);
Transaction transaction = datastore.newTransaction();
transaction.get(KEY2);
transaction.update(Entity.builder(ENTITY1).clear().set("from", "transaction").build());
// update during the transaction
datastore.update(Entity.builder(ENTITY1).clear().set("from", "datastore").build());
transaction.commit();
```
I get different exceptions if I am running against the emulator (`v1.2.0`) or the actual service (`v1`).
* **Emulator**:
`com.google.datastore.v1.client.DatastoreException: too much contention on these datastore entities. please try again., code=ABORTED`
* **Actual Service**:
`com.google.datastore.v1.client.DatastoreException: transaction closed, code=INVALID_ARGUMENT`

Do you have any idea why this is happening? I believe the correct error should be `ABORTED`, right?

This is the (node.js) code I'm using to query (from a simple datastore with just a single entity):

Datastore = require('@google-cloud/datastore');
projectId = '<my-project-id>';

datastoreClient = Datastore({
  projectId: projectId
});

var query = datastoreClient.createQuery('Test').limit(1);

console.time('query');
query.run(function (err, test) {
  if (err) {
    console.log(err);
    return;
  }
  console.timeEnd('query');
});

The first request takes > 2 sec and the subsequent requests are still faster.
If you wait 4 minutes or more between requests, query times are back to >2 secs.

